9 An Act relating to the Incentive Evaluation
Commission; amending 62 O.S. 2021, Section 7005, as
10 amended by Section 3, Chapter 125, O.S.L. 2023 (62
O.S. Supp. 2025, Section 7005), which relates to the
11 evaluation process; requiring the Commission to
submit report to the Secretary of State; modifying
12 required considerations for estimate of economic and
fiscal impact; updating statutory language; and
13 updating statutory references.
14
15
16 BE IT ENACTED BY THE PEOPLE OF THE STATE OF OKLAHOMA:
17 SECTION 1. AMENDATORY 62 O.S. 2021, Section 7005, as
18 amended by Section 3, Chapter 125, O.S.L. 2023 (62 O.S. Supp. 2025,
19 Section 7005), is amended to read as follows:
20 Section 7005. A. The Incentive Evaluation Commission may
21 contract with a private company, nonprofit, or academic institution
22 to assist with evaluation of each incentive. The Commission shall
23 develop a scope of services for a request for proposals issued
24 pursuant to the Oklahoma Central Purchasing Act, Section 85.1 et
SB1990 HFLR Page 1
BOLD FACE denotes Committee Amendments.

1 seq. of Title 74 of the Oklahoma Statutes, for professional services
2 necessary to complete incentive evaluations pursuant to the
3 Incentive Evaluation Act. The scope of services shall include a
4 provision requiring the contractor to provide at least one draft
5 report for each incentive prior to the issuance of the final report;
6 provided, the contractor may determine the timing and frequency of
7 draft reports based on the availability of information and the
8 potential for draft reports to assist the Commission in making a
9 final recommendation. The cost of such contract shall be paid by
10 the Office of Management and Enterprise Services. No recipient or
11 potential recipient of an incentive or representative of a recipient
12 or potential recipient shall contact the entity or individual with
13 whom the Commission contracts pursuant to this subsection unless the
14 entity or individual specifically requests information or
15 documentation for purposes of the incentive evaluation process;
16 provided, this shall not be construed to prevent participation in a
17 public hearing conducted pursuant to subsection B of this section.
18 B. By October 1 of each year beginning in calendar year 2023,
19 the Commission or the Commission’s chosen contractor shall evaluate
20 each incentive scheduled for review that year. The Commission or
21 the Commission’s chosen contractor shall conduct each incentive
22 evaluation in consultation with the Oklahoma Department of Commerce
23 division of Policy, Research and Economic Analysis Services Division
24 using criteria developed pursuant to subsection D of this section.
SB1990 HFLR Page 2
BOLD FACE denotes Committee Amendments.

1 Betw een October 1 and November 30 of each year beginning in 2017,
2 the Commission shall hold at least one public meeting to review,
3 allow for public comment, and vote to approve, disapprove, or modify
4 each incentive evaluation conducted that year. By December 15 of
5 each year beginning in 2016, the Commission shall provide the
6 results of each incentive evaluation, a review of prior Commission
7 recommendations, and changes to statute or incentive administration
8 related to incentive evaluation recommendations in a written report
9 submitted electronically to the Governor, President Pro Tempore of
10 the Senate, and Speaker of the House of Representatives, and the
11 Secretary of State. If the Commission votes to modify an incentive
12 evaluation as provided in this subsection, such modification and the
13 original evaluation shall be documented in the annual written report
14 submitted electronically. The report shall be made publicly
15 available on the Oklahoma Department of Commerce website, the
16 Commission website, and documents.ok.gov.
17 C. Each evaluation shall include the following:
18 1. An estimate of the economic and fiscal impact of the
19 incentive. This estimate shall take into account the following
20 considerations in addition to other relevant factors:
21 a. the extent to which the incentive changes business
22 behavior, including whether a business receiving the
23 incentive would likely have taken any action required
24
SB1990 HFLR Page 3
BOLD FACE denotes Committee Amendments.

1 to receive the incentive in the absence of such
2 incentive,
3 b. the results of the incentive for the economy of
4 Oklahoma as a whole. This consideration includes both
5 positive direct and indirect impacts and any negative
6 effects on other Oklahoma businesses, and
7 c. a comparison to the results of other incentives or
8 other economic development strategies with similar
9 goals both within this state and other states;
10 2. An assessment of whether adequate protections are in place
11 to ensure the fiscal impact of the incentive does not increase
12 substantially beyond the state’s expectations in future years;
13 3. An assessment of whether the incentive is being administered
14 effectively;
15 4. An assessment of whether the incentive is achieving its
16 goals;
17 5. Recommendations for how the state can most effectively
18 achieve the incentive’s goals, including recommendations on whether
19 the incentive should be retained, reconfigured, or repealed; and
20 6. Recommendations for any changes to state policy, rules, or
21 statutes that would allow the incentive to be more easily or
22 conclusively evaluated in the future. These recommendations may
23 include changes to collection, reporting, and sharing of data, and
24 revisions or clarifications to the goal of the incentive;
SB1990 HFLR Page 4
BOLD FACE denotes Committee Amendments.

1 7. An assessment of whether the incentive furthers a strategic
2 economic goal or an industry within this state; and
3 8. An assessment of whether the incentive creates a competitive
4 advantage for this state by evaluating the overall effectiveness of
5 the incentive at a macroeconomic level.
6 D. Evaluation criteria shall be developed for each incentive
7 evaluated by the Commission. Each incentive shall be evaluated
8 using criteria specific to the individual incentive. The criteria
9 shall be developed by the Commission through the administrative
10 rulemaking process pursuant to the Administrative Procedures Act,
11 Section 250 et seq. of Title 75 of the Oklahoma Statutes, and
12 codified in the administrative code of the Oklahoma Department of
13 Commerce.
14 E. At the request of the Incentive Evaluation Commission,
15 unless prohibited by the Oklahoma Constitution, Oklahoma Statutes,
16 or federal law, state agencies shall provide any records,
17 information, data, or data analysis necessary for the Commission or
18 contractors to effectively evaluate incentives. The Commission and
19 contractors shall not disclose or release any data received from
20 other state agencies, except as permitted under law.
